<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="6" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,438,1579]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,266,438,463]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Diagnosis</emphasis>
. Adult female body highly transformed consisting of ectosoma connected to endosoma by broad stalk passing through host’s body wall. Endosoma embedded in host, elongate, filiform. Ectosoma globular to slightly dorsoventrally flattened; lacking any external trace of segmentation. Genital apertures paired, carried on sclerotized areas of cuticle located posterolaterally on margin of ectosoma; median copulatory pore located between genital apertures on ventral surface of ectosoma. Lacking vestiges of appendages and caudal rami; without anus. Egg sacs paired, large, multiseriate.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,438,1579]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Adult male consisting of broad, subquadrate cephalothorax and slender postcephalic trunk. Caudal rami modified as pair of hooks. Antennule indistinctly 3-segmented; third segment offset posterolaterally; first segment with blunt, modified setal element; second segment with 2 setal elements; distal segment with 2 apical elements. Antenna uniramous and subchelate, comprising elongate proximal segment, plus distal endopodal segment bearing terminal claw plus accessory claw. Mandible absent. Maxillule small, lobate, bearing 2 apical setae. Maxilla lobate, ornamented with denticles distally. Maxilliped subchelate; proximal segment robust, ornamented with 2 spinulose processes on myxal surface; distal subchela comprising free endopodal segment plus curved claw.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,945,906,931]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" type="materials_examined">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,438,1579]" box="[199,945,906,931]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,347,906,931]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">
<typeStatus box="[199,258,906,931]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Type</typeStatus>
species
</emphasis>
: 
<taxonomicName authority="Levinsen, 1878" authorityName="Levinsen" authorityYear="1878" box="[362,779,906,931]" class="Hexanauplia" family="Bradophilidae" genus="Bradophila" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyclopoida" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pygmaea">
<emphasis box="[362,597,906,931]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Bradophila pygmaea</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Levinsen, G. M. R." box="[604,779,906,931]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" pagination="351 - 380" refId="ref47405" refString="Levinsen, G. M. R. (1878) Om nogle parasitiske Krebsdyr, der snylte hos Annelider. Fidenskalbelige Meddelelser fra dansk Naturhistorisk Forening I KJObenhavn, 1877 - 78, 351 - 380, pl. 6." type="journal article" year="1878">Levinsen, 1878</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, by monotypy.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="6" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,438,1579]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,942,967]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Remarks.</emphasis>
Since its original description 140 years ago, the 
<typeStatus box="[872,920,943,967]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">type</typeStatus>
species, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Levinsen" authorityYear="1878" box="[1024,1158,943,966]" class="Hexanauplia" family="Bradophilidae" genus="Bradophila" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyclopoida" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pygmaea">
<emphasis box="[1024,1158,943,966]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">B. pygmaea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, has been reported from only a single host species, 
<taxonomicName authority="(Rathke, 1843)" authorityName="Rathke" authorityYear="1843" baseAuthorityName="Rathke" baseAuthorityYear="1843" box="[464,801,978,1003]" class="Polychaeta" family="Flabelligeridae" genus="Brada" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="villosa">
<emphasis box="[464,619,978,1003]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Brada villosa</emphasis>
(Rathke, 1843)
</taxonomicName>
, a member of the polychaete family 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Saint-Joseph" authorityYear="1894" box="[1231,1399,978,1003]" class="Polychaeta" family="Flabelligeridae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Annelida" rank="family">Flabelligeridae</taxonomicName>
de Saint Joseph, 1894. The original description was based on museum material with no locality data (
<bibRefCitation author="Levinsen, G. M. R." box="[1259,1428,1014,1039]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" pagination="351 - 380" refId="ref47405" refString="Levinsen, G. M. R. (1878) Om nogle parasitiske Krebsdyr, der snylte hos Annelider. Fidenskalbelige Meddelelser fra dansk Naturhistorisk Forening I KJObenhavn, 1877 - 78, 351 - 380, pl. 6." type="journal article" year="1878">Levinsen 1878</bibRefCitation>
) but its known distribution is restricted to high latitude waters of the North Atlantic including both Norwegian and Russian coastal waters and into the White Sea (
<bibRefCitation author="Marchenkov, A. V." box="[741,959,1086,1111]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" refId="ref47852" refString="Marchenkov, A. V. (1999) Symbiotic and parasitic Crustacea off benthic marine invertebrates from the Arctic Seas of Russia. Unpublished PhD thesis, Zoological Institute, Russian Academy of Sciences, Saint Petersburg, 193 pp." type="book" year="1999">Marchenkov 1999</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Huys, R." box="[977,1112,1086,1111]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" pagination="355 - 385" refId="ref47088" refString="Huys, R. (2016) Enigmas from the past: M'Intosh's (1885) annelidicolous copepods from the voyage of H. M. S. Challenger. Zootaxa, 4174 (1), 355 - 385. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4174.1.22" type="journal article" year="2016">Huys 2016</bibRefCitation>
). 
<bibRefCitation author="Marchenkov, A. V." box="[1138,1369,1086,1111]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" pagination="514 - 516" refId="ref47894" refString="Marchenkov, A. V. (2002) Bradophilidae fam. nov. - the new family of mesoparasitic copepod collected from the polychaete Brada villosa from the White Sea. Parazitologiya, 36 (6), 514 - 516." type="journal article" year="2002">Marchenkov (2002)</bibRefCitation>
gave supplementary morphological data on the female of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Levinsen" authorityYear="1878" box="[750,884,1124,1147]" class="Hexanauplia" family="Bradophilidae" genus="Bradophila" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyclopoida" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pygmaea">
<emphasis box="[750,884,1124,1147]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">B. pygmaea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
: its globular, slightly flattened ectosoma ranged from 
<quantity box="[213,373,1158,1183]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.0" metricValueMax="7.0" metricValueMin="5.0" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" unit="mm" value="0.6" valueMax="0.7" valueMin="0.5">0.5 to 0.7 mm</quantity>
in diameter; the egg sacs were up to 
<quantity box="[797,884,1159,1183]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.2" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" unit="mm" value="1.2">1.2 mm</quantity>
long and varied in width from 
<quantity box="[1239,1402,1159,1183]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.5" metricValueMax="7.0" metricValueMin="4.0" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" unit="mm" value="0.55" valueMax="0.7" valueMin="0.4">0.4 to 0.7 mm</quantity>
; in live specimens the colour of the ectosoma was translucent or milky white. 
<bibRefCitation author="Marchenkov, A. V." box="[1017,1243,1194,1219]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" pagination="514 - 516" refId="ref47894" refString="Marchenkov, A. V. (2002) Bradophilidae fam. nov. - the new family of mesoparasitic copepod collected from the polychaete Brada villosa from the White Sea. Parazitologiya, 36 (6), 514 - 516." type="journal article" year="2002">Marchenkov (2002)</bibRefCitation>
stressed that the posterolaterally-located, paired genital apertures of the female were relatively inconspicuous. He also described the endosoma as elongate with its entire surface covered with small tubercles and this was confirmed by 
<bibRefCitation author="Huys, R." box="[1288,1432,1266,1291]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" pagination="355 - 385" refId="ref47088" refString="Huys, R. (2016) Enigmas from the past: M'Intosh's (1885) annelidicolous copepods from the voyage of H. M. S. Challenger. Zootaxa, 4174 (1), 355 - 385. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4174.1.22" type="journal article" year="2016">Huys (2016)</bibRefCitation>
. However, as noted by 
<bibRefCitation author="Huys, R." box="[402,546,1302,1327]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" pagination="355 - 385" refId="ref47088" refString="Huys, R. (2016) Enigmas from the past: M'Intosh's (1885) annelidicolous copepods from the voyage of H. M. S. Challenger. Zootaxa, 4174 (1), 355 - 385. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4174.1.22" type="journal article" year="2016">Huys (2016)</bibRefCitation>
, the size of the ectosoma of the female given by 
<bibRefCitation author="Levinsen, G. M. R." box="[1095,1280,1302,1327]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" pagination="351 - 380" refId="ref47405" refString="Levinsen, G. M. R. (1878) Om nogle parasitiske Krebsdyr, der snylte hos Annelider. Fidenskalbelige Meddelelser fra dansk Naturhistorisk Forening I KJObenhavn, 1877 - 78, 351 - 380, pl. 6." type="journal article" year="1878">Levinsen (1878)</bibRefCitation>
was 
<quantity metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.15" metricValueMax="5.0" metricValueMin="3.3" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" unit="mm" value="415.0" valueMax="500.0" valueMin="330.0">330–500 µm</quantity>
, which is considerably smaller than that reported by 
<bibRefCitation author="Marchenkov, A. V." box="[782,1008,1338,1363]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" pagination="514 - 516" refId="ref47894" refString="Marchenkov, A. V. (2002) Bradophilidae fam. nov. - the new family of mesoparasitic copepod collected from the polychaete Brada villosa from the White Sea. Parazitologiya, 36 (6), 514 - 516." type="journal article" year="2002">Marchenkov (2002)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,438,1579]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">
The male of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Levinsen" authorityYear="1878" box="[341,473,1375,1398]" class="Hexanauplia" family="Bradophilidae" genus="Bradophila" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyclopoida" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pygmaea">
<emphasis box="[341,473,1375,1398]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">B. pygmaea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was attached in the vicinity of the stalk of the female by means of its modified caudal rami, antennae and maxillipeds (
<bibRefCitation author="Marchenkov, A. V." box="[520,733,1410,1435]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" pagination="514 - 516" refId="ref47894" refString="Marchenkov, A. V. (2002) Bradophilidae fam. nov. - the new family of mesoparasitic copepod collected from the polychaete Brada villosa from the White Sea. Parazitologiya, 36 (6), 514 - 516." type="journal article" year="2002">Marchenkov 2002</bibRefCitation>
). Marchenkov gave the male body length as 
<quantity box="[1241,1432,1410,1435]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" metricValueMax="4.5" metricValueMin="3.5" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" unit="mm" value="0.4" valueMax="0.45" valueMin="0.35">0.35 to 0.45 mm</quantity>
, with a maximum width at the cephalosome of 
<quantity box="[668,855,1446,1471]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.75" metricValueMax="2.0" metricValueMin="1.5" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" unit="mm" value="0.175" valueMax="0.2" valueMin="0.15">0.15 to 0.20 mm</quantity>
. 
<bibRefCitation author="Huys, R." box="[866,1006,1446,1471]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" pagination="355 - 385" refId="ref47088" refString="Huys, R. (2016) Enigmas from the past: M'Intosh's (1885) annelidicolous copepods from the voyage of H. M. S. Challenger. Zootaxa, 4174 (1), 355 - 385. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4174.1.22" type="journal article" year="2016">Huys (2016)</bibRefCitation>
examined material of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Levinsen" authorityYear="1878" box="[1257,1389,1447,1470]" class="Hexanauplia" family="Bradophilidae" genus="Bradophila" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyclopoida" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pygmaea">
<emphasis box="[1257,1389,1447,1470]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">B. pygmaea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and described the male as 
<quantity box="[404,492,1482,1507]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.3" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" unit="mm" value="530.0">530 µm</quantity>
in length with a maximum width of 
<quantity box="[915,992,1483,1507]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.3" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" unit="mm" value="93.0">93 µm</quantity>
. The structure and setation of the male limbs were described by 
<bibRefCitation author="Marchenkov, A. V." box="[447,678,1518,1543]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" pagination="514 - 516" refId="ref47894" refString="Marchenkov, A. V. (2002) Bradophilidae fam. nov. - the new family of mesoparasitic copepod collected from the polychaete Brada villosa from the White Sea. Parazitologiya, 36 (6), 514 - 516." type="journal article" year="2002">Marchenkov (2002)</bibRefCitation>
, and again more recently by 
<bibRefCitation author="Huys, R." box="[1026,1171,1518,1543]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" pagination="355 - 385" refId="ref47088" refString="Huys, R. (2016) Enigmas from the past: M'Intosh's (1885) annelidicolous copepods from the voyage of H. M. S. Challenger. Zootaxa, 4174 (1), 355 - 385. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4174.1.22" type="journal article" year="2016">Huys (2016)</bibRefCitation>
who corrected several misinterpretations made by 
<bibRefCitation author="Marchenkov, A. V." box="[463,689,1554,1579]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" pagination="514 - 516" refId="ref47894" refString="Marchenkov, A. V. (2002) Bradophilidae fam. nov. - the new family of mesoparasitic copepod collected from the polychaete Brada villosa from the White Sea. Parazitologiya, 36 (6), 514 - 516." type="journal article" year="2002">Marchenkov (2002)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
